Description: Defer annotations + spell out RequestContext defaults on Noble
 mcp 1.27.1 declares its third `RequestContext` TypeVar with
 `default=Any` via `typing_extensions.TypeVar`, then subscripts the
 class with only two type arguments at several module-import-time
 sites. Filling in the missing third argument from the TypeVar's
 default requires typing_extensions >= 4.12, which patches Python's
 stock `Generic.__class_getitem__` so it consults
 `typing_extensions.TypeVar.__default__`. Noble's archive ships
 typing_extensions 4.10, which exposes the `default=` keyword but
 does not patch `__class_getitem__`, so `import mcp` raises
 `TypeError: Too few arguments for RequestContext; actual 2,
 expected 3` on Noble.
 .
 Two targeted changes avoid the bump:
 .
 * Add `from __future__ import annotations` to the three modules
   whose type-annotation subscripts trip the runtime check
   (`mcp.client.session`, `mcp.client.experimental.task_handlers`,
   `mcp.shared.progress`). With PEP 563 in effect the annotations
   are stored as strings rather than evaluated at class definition,
   matching what every modern typechecker already does and removing
   the dependency on typing_extensions' `__class_getitem__` patch
   for these annotations.
 * Patch one remaining runtime call site in
   `mcp/client/session.py:_received_request`, where
   `RequestContext[ClientSession, Any]` is built at call time (not
   inside an annotation). PEP 563 cannot help there; spell out the
   third TypeVar explicitly as `Any` so the subscription is valid
   under Noble's typing_extensions. Behaviour is identical because
   that is exactly the value the default would supply.
 .
 Static type-checker output is unaffected (`Any` is the declared
 default; `from __future__ import annotations` only changes
 evaluation timing). Drop this patch once Noble ships
 typing_extensions >= 4.12.
Author: Avalan Packaging Team <avalan@avalan.ai>
Forwarded: not-needed
Last-Update: 2026-05-20

